    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>For <strong>Mac</strong> Users, the shortcut is </p>\n\n<p><strong><kbd>^</kbd>(control) + <kbd>h</kbd></strong></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1062360,
      "reputation" : 39802,
      "user_id" : 1063716,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 94,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/594dfa12a4f922652c182c46b6bc2de3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Steve Chambers",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1063716/steve-chambers"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1537342071,
    "last_edit_date" : 1537342071,
    "creation_date" : 1523346288,
    "answer_id" : 49748079,
    "question_id" : 3990781,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Whilst Eclipse includes the type hierarchy and class structure (methods, fields etc.) in a single view, IntelliJ splits these up: In addition to the <kbd>CTRL</kbd>+<kbd>H</kbd> (or <kbd>ALT</kbd>+<kbd>8</kbd>) <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/building-class-hierarchy.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">\"Type Hierarchy\"</a> view, the other relevant IntelliJ window is called <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/viewing-structure-of-a-source-file.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">\"Structure\"</a> and can be invoked via <kbd>ALT</kbd>+<kbd>7</kbd> (Structure Tool Window) or <kbd>CTRL</kbd>+<kbd>F12</kbd>(Structure popup).</p>\n\n<p><em>(Not a direct answer to the exact question posted but would expect others from an Eclipse background may arrive here having googled for \"intellij type hierarchy\", as I did.)</em></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 20693,
      "reputation" : 21551,
      "user_id" : 1423922,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 79,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04bc578d30953f3906ba64db9ac69aa5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Konstantin Spirin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1423922/konstantin-spirin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1542870550,
    "creation_date" : 1542870550,
    "answer_id" : 53425562,
    "question_id" : 3990781,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><kbd>Ctrl+U</kbd> - go to base class</p>\n\n<p><kbd>Ctrl+Alt+B</kbd> - got to implementation. Type parts of class name to narrow down the list</p>\n\n<p><kbd>Ctrl+H</kbd> - open type hierarchy tool window</p>\n\n<p><kbd>Ctrl+Alt+U</kbd> - peek class/interface inheritance hierarchy</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 100270,
      "reputation" : 132415,
      "user_id" : 270371,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 33,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/LSTUa.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "davidxxx",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/270371/davidxxx"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1544452088,
    "creation_date" : 1544452088,
    "answer_id" : 53707709,
    "question_id" : 3990781,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>With Eclipse, hitting <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> on a type displays its subtypes and hit again <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> displays so supertypes.  And so for... this is a toggle.<br>\nThat is really helpful and also very straight.    </p>\n\n<p>Unfortunately with IntelliJ, the switch between the supertypes and the subtypes doesn't have any default shortcut.  So you will have to click on the icons of the hierarchy windows.<br>\nIf like me you favor the keyboard shortcuts to the \"move cursor and click on mouse\" option, I encourage you to set a binding for these two operations.  For example  <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Down</kbd>  for subtypes and  <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Up</kbd>  for supertypes.    </p>\n\n<p>Where you can change the binding (\"Bas\" means \"Down\" and \"Haut\" means \"Up\") : \n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/iO59l.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/iO59l.png\" alt=\"biding\"></a></p>\n\n<p>Note that these bindings are contextual to the <strong>\"Other\"</strong> context (Eclipse does have a similar enough concept). \n1) In this way, enter <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> on a <code>ArrayList</code> type produces :</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/7NSrW.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/7NSrW.png\" alt=\"Default hierarchy\"></a></p>\n\n<p>2) Enter <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Down</kbd> focuses on subtypes :</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/GxubU.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/GxubU.png\" alt=\"subtypes focus\"></a></p>\n\n<p>3) And Enter <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Up</kbd> focuses on supertypes :</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/GxubU.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/GxubU.png\" alt=\"supertypes focus\"></a></p>\n\n<p>In this way, I find it better than the default behavior but to be honest even with that shortcut adding, the IntelliJ feature is not as good as Eclipse which the  <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>T</kbd> shortcut also works on methods...</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8665771,
      "reputation" : 11,
      "user_id" : 6486373,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-q24GElBflUA/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAk5g/OYx9tFSgbj4/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "herberlin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6486373/herberlin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1575827333,
    "creation_date" : 1575827333,
    "answer_id" : 59238179,
    "question_id" : 3990781,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is a hierarchy view as in Eclipse, have a look at the menu View / Tool Windows / Hierarchy or press Alt-8 or F4. </p>\n"
  }, {
